{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5deb59a-ffe6-4e26-8ca3-e5204c4e207a","content":"Use conditional compilation or the `AddPlatformSpecific` pattern in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService>(\n#if ANDROID\n    new AndroidNotificationService()\n#elif IOS\n    new iOSNotificationService()\n#elif WINDOWS\n    new WindowsNotificationService()\n#endif\n);\n```\n\n**Or** use partial classes with the platform folders approach (preferred for cleaner separation):\n\n1. Define your interface in shared code.\n2. Place implementations in `Platforms/Android/`, `Platforms/iOS/`, `Platforms/Windows/`.\n3. Register without `#if` directives:\n\n```csharp\n// MauiProgram.cs\nbuilder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();\n```\n\nThen create a partial class `NotificationService` in each platform folder — the build system compiles only the relevant one per target.\n\nThis won't break on any platform because each target only sees its own implementation file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f06e3ed6-9690-4d68-9d70-73548a659dfd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` interface in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code change in a repository.","outputTokens":316,"requestId":"9823:30FF5A:15BD856:185F504:6A052001"},"id":"11f3d6d6-42d3-4661-a414-0712eda3c9e3","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:07:51.482Z","parentId":"8424a225-3261-462f-b616-2d049e553738"}
